Flask Architecture

Flask applications follow a request-response architecture.
User or Browser
       |
       | HTTP Request
       v
Web Server / Flask Application
       |
       | URL Routing
       v
Python View Function
       |
       | Business Logic
       v
Template / Database / API
       |
       | HTTP Response
       v
User or Browser



A small Flask application may use the following structure:
flask_employee_app/
│
├── app.py
├── employee.txt
├── requirements.txt
│
├── templates/
│   ├── index.html
│   ├── employees.html
│   └── add_employee.html
│
└── static/
    ├── css/
    │   └── style.css
    │
    ├── js/
    │   └── script.js
    │
    └── images/
        └── logo.png





Request-Response Flow

Consider this URL:
http://127.0.0.1:5000/employees
The application processes it through the following steps:
The browser sends an HTTP request.
Flask receives the request.
Flask checks the URL routing table.
Flask identifies the matching view function.
The view function executes the required logic.
The view function returns a response.
Flask sends the response to the browser.
Flask automatically creates a request context while processing each incoming request. 
This allows the application to access request-related information through objects such as request and session.





Important Flask Components

Component
Purpose
Flask application
Main web application object
Route
Connects a URL to a Python function
View function
Processes a request and generates a response
Request object
Contains data sent by the client
Response object
Contains data returned to the client
Template
Generates dynamic HTML
Static files
Stores CSS, JavaScript, images, and other resources
Jinja
Flask’s template-rendering engine
Werkzeug
Provides request, response, and routing utilities


Flask also installs supporting libraries such as Werkzeug, Jinja, Click, ItsDangerous and Blinker.


